the pore wall. It effectively measures the hydrophobicity
of the wall. This becomes even more apparent when the (macroscopic) contact angle cos θe = γw/γlv is formally computed (table 1). Macroscopically, a hydrophobic surface can be deﬁned as one with θe > 90◦. This allows us to call the apolar pore (θe = 134◦) ‘hydrophobic’ compared to the ‘amphipathic’ pore D2 (θe = 111◦; still hydrophobic but with some ‘hydrophilic’ patches). A ‘hydrophilic’ pore like the D4 system (θe ≈ 51◦) is characterized by γw > 0 or θe < 90◦ and liquid is always the preferred phase in the pore, regardless
of R.
